name: MessageLookupByLibrary
comment: This provides an abstract class for messages looked up in generated code. Each locale will have a separate subclass of this class with its set of messages. See generate_localized.dart.

localeName.name: localeName
localeName.comment: Subclasses should override this to return their locale, e.g. 'en_US'

messages.name: messages
messages.comment: Subclasses should override this to return a list of their message functions.

[].comment: Return our message with the given name

lookupMessage.name: lookupMessage
lookupMessage.comment:
Return the localized version of a message. We are passed the original version of the message, which consists of a intl/message_lookup_by_library.MessageLookupByLibrary.lookupMessage.message_str that will be translated, and which may be interpolated based on one or more variables, a intl/message_lookup_by_library.MessageLookupByLibrary.lookupMessage.desc providing a description of usage for the intl/message_lookup_by_library.MessageLookupByLibrary.lookupMessage.message_str, and a map of intl/message_lookup_by_library.MessageLookupByLibrary.lookupMessage.examples for each data element to be substituted into the message.

For example, if message="Hello, $name", then examples = {'name': 'Sparky'}. If not using the user's default locale, or if the locale is not easily detectable, explicitly pass intl/message_lookup_by_library.MessageLookupByLibrary.lookupMessage.locale.

The values of intl/message_lookup_by_library.MessageLookupByLibrary.lookupMessage.desc and intl/message_lookup_by_library.MessageLookupByLibrary.lookupMessage.examples are not used at run-time but are only made available to the translators, so they MUST be simple Strings available at compile time: no String interpolation or concatenation. The expected usage of this is inside a function that takes as parameters the variables used in the interpolated string.

Ultimately, the information about the enclosing function and its arguments will be extracted automatically but for the time being it must be passed explicitly in the intl/message_lookup_by_library.MessageLookupByLibrary.lookupMessage.name and intl/message_lookup_by_library.MessageLookupByLibrary.lookupMessage.args arguments.

toString.name: toString
toString.comment: Returns a string representation of this object.

hashCode.name: hashCode
hashCode.comment:
Get a hash code for this object.

All objects have hash codes. Hash codes are guaranteed to be the same for objects that are equal when compared using the equality operator ==. Other than that there are no guarantees about the hash codes. They will not be consistent between runs and there are no distribution guarantees.

If a subclass overrides intl/message_lookup_by_library.MessageLookupByLibrary.hashCode it should override the equality operator as well to maintain consistency.

runtimeType.name: runtimeType
runtimeType.comment: A representation of the runtime type of the object.

==.comment:
The equality operator.

The default behavior for all dart-core.Objects is to return true if and only if this and intl/message_lookup_by_library.MessageLookupByLibrary.==.other are the same object.

Override this method to specify a different equality relation on a class. The overriding method must still be an equivalence relation. That is, it must be:

  • Total: It must return a boolean for all arguments. It should never throw or return null.

  • Reflexive: For all objects o, o == o must be true.

  • Symmetric: For all objects o1 and o2, o1 == o2 and o2 == o1 must either both be true, or both be false.

  • Transitive: For all objects o1, o2, and o3, if o1 == o2 and o2 == o3 are true, then o1 == o3 must be true.

The method should also be consistent over time, so equality of two objects should not change over time, or at least only change if one of the objects was modified.

If a subclass overrides the equality operator it should override the intl/message_lookup_by_library.MessageLookupByLibrary.hashCode method as well to maintain consistency.

noSuchMethod.name: noSuchMethod
noSuchMethod.comment:
intl/message_lookup_by_library.MessageLookupByLibrary.noSuchMethod is invoked when users invoke a non-existent method on an object. The name of the method and the arguments of the invocation are passed to intl/message_lookup_by_library.MessageLookupByLibrary.noSuchMethod in an dart-core.Invocation. If intl/message_lookup_by_library.MessageLookupByLibrary.noSuchMethod returns a value, that value becomes the result of the original invocation.

The default behavior of intl/message_lookup_by_library.MessageLookupByLibrary.noSuchMethod is to throw a dart-core.NoSuchMethodError.

toString.name: toString
toString.comment: Returns a string representation of this object.
